{"title_page": "K\u00fcbler-Ross model", "text_new": "[[File:Kubler-ross-grief-cycle-1-728.jpg|thumb|400px|The five stages of grief according to the K\u00fcbler-Ross model]]\n\nThe '''K\u00fcbler-Ross model''', or the '''five stages of grief''', postulates a series of emotions experienced by terminally ill patients prior to [[death]], or people who have lost a loved one, wherein the five stages are: [[denial]], [[anger]], bargaining, [[Depression (mood)|depression]],  and [[acceptance]]. Although commonly referenced in popular media, the existence of these stages has not been demonstrated and the model is not considered helpful in explaining the grieving process.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Bonanno2009\" />\n\nThe model was first introduced by Swiss-American psychiatrist [[Elisabeth K\u00fcbler-Ross]] in her 1969 book ''[[On Death and Dying]]'', and was inspired by her work with [[Terminal illness|terminally ill]] patients.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,689491,00.html |title= Milestones |date=August 30, 2004 | work=TIME | first=Sarah M. | last=Broom | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> Motivated by the lack of instruction in medical schools on the subject of death and dying, K\u00fcbler-Ross examined death and those faced with it at the [[University of Chicago]]'s [[Pritzker School of Medicine|medical school]]. K\u00fcbler-Ross's project evolved into a series of seminars which, along with patient interviews and previous research, became the foundation for her book.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uky.edu/~cperring/kr.htm |title=PHI350: The Stages in the Dying Process |first=Christian |last=Perring | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Although K\u00fcbler-Ross is commonly credited with creating stage models, earlier  bereavement theorists and clinicians such as [[Erich Lindemann]], [[Colin Murray Parkes|Collin Murray Parkes]], and [[John Bowlby]] used similar models of stages of phases as early as the 1940s.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Bereavement groups and the role of social support: integrating theory, research, and practice |last=Hoy |first=William G. | name-list-format = vanc |date=2016 |publisher=Routledge/Taylor and Francis |isbn=9781317416357 |location=New York |oclc=942843686}}</ref>\n\nLater in her life, K\u00fcbler-Ross noted that the stages are not a linear and predictable progression and that she regretted writing them in a way that was misunderstood.<ref name=GriefGrieving /> \"K\u00fcbler-Ross originally saw these stages as reflecting how people cope with illness and dying,\" observed grief researcher Kenneth J. Doka, \"not as reflections of how people grieve.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = Doka | first = Kenneth J. | name-list-format = vanc | title = Grief Is a Journey: Finding Your Path Through Loss | publisher = Simon and Schuster | date = 2016 | page = 6 }}</ref>\n\n== Stages of grief in terminal illness ==\n[[File:K\u00fcbler Ross grieving curve (edited).png|thumb|A diagram developed by Bertrand Grondin from a presentation of Elisabeth K\u00fcbler Ross ideas produced by [[France Telecom]]]]\n[[File:K\u00fcbler Ross's stages of grief.png|thumb|Diagram showing two possible outcomes of grief or a life-changing event developed for [[Jobcentre Plus]] by Eos]]\n\nThe stages, popularly known by the acronym '''DABDA''', include:<ref name=\"Santrock\">{{cite book |title=A Topical Approach to Life-Span Development | vauthors = Santrock JW |year= 2007 |publisher= [[McGraw-Hill]] |location= New York |isbn= 978-0-07-338264-7 |page= |pages= |url= |access-date=}}{{page needed|date=May 2014}}</ref>\n#[[Denial]] \u2013 The first reaction is denial. In this stage, individuals believe the diagnosis is somehow mistaken, and cling to a false, preferable reality.\n#[[Anger]] \u2013 When the individual recognizes that denial cannot continue, they become frustrated, especially at proximate individuals. Certain psychological responses of a person undergoing this phase would be: \"Why me? It's not fair!\"; \"How can this happen to me?\"; \"Who is to blame?\"; \"Why would this happen?\".\n#[[Bargaining]] \u2013 The third stage involves the hope that the individual can avoid a cause of grief. Usually, the negotiation for an extended life is made in exchange for a reformed lifestyle. People facing less serious trauma can bargain or seek compromise. Examples include the terminally ill person who \"negotiates with God\" to attend a daughter's wedding, an attempt to bargain for more time to live in exchange for a reformed lifestyle or a phrase such as \"If I could trade their life for mine\".\n#[[Depression (mood)|Depression]] \u2013 \"I'm so sad, why bother with anything?\"; \"I'm going to die soon, so what's the point?\"; \"I miss my loved one; why go on?\"<br />During the fourth stage, the individual despairs at the recognition of their mortality. In this state, the individual may become silent, refuse visitors and spend much of the time mournful and sullen.\n#[[Acceptance]] \u2013 \"It's going to be okay.\"; \"I can't fight it; I may as well prepare for it.\"<br /> In this last stage, individuals embrace mortality or inevitable future, or that of a loved one, or other tragic event. People dying may precede the survivors in this state, which typically comes with a calm, retrospective view for the individual, and a stable condition of emotions.\n\nIn a book co-authored with [[David_Kessler_(writer)|David Kessler]] and published posthumously, K\u00fcbler-Ross expanded her model to include any form of personal loss, such as the death of a loved one, the loss of a job or income, major [[Social rejection|rejection]], the end of a relationship or [[divorce]], [[drug addiction]], [[incarceration]], the onset of a [[disease]] or an [[infertility]] diagnosis, and even minor losses, such as a loss of insurance coverage.<ref name=GriefGrieving>{{Cite book |title=On grief & grieving : finding the meaning of grief through the five stages of loss |last=K\u00fcbler-Ross |first=Elisabeth |date=2014 |publisher=Scribner |last2=Kessler |first2=David | name-list-format = vanc |isbn=9781476775555 |location=New York |oclc=863077888}}</ref> Kessler has also proposed \"Meaning\" as a sixth stage of grief.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H920DwAAQBAJ |title = Finding Meaning: The Sixth Stage of Grief|isbn = 9781501192739|last1 = Kessler|first1 = David|date = 5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nCriticisms of this five-stage model of grief center mainly on a lack of [[empirical research]] and [[empirical evidence]] supporting the stages as described by K\u00fcbler-Ross and, to the contrary, empirical support for other modes of the expression of grief. Moreover, K\u00fcbler-Ross' model is the product of a particular culture at a particular time and might not be applicable to people of other cultures. These points have been made by many experts,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Stroebe M, Schut H, Boerner K | title = Cautioning Health-Care Professionals | journal = Omega | volume = 74 | issue = 4 | pages = 455\u2013473 | date = March 2017 | pmid = 28355991 | pmc = 5375020 | doi = 10.1177/0030222817691870 }}</ref> such as Professor Robert J. Kastenbaum (1932\u20132013) who was a recognized expert in gerontology, aging, and death. In his writings, Kastenbaum raised the following points:<ref>{{cite book | last = Kastenbaum | first = Robert | name-list-format = vanc | title = Death, Society, and Human Experience | edition = 6th | location = Boston | publisher = Allyn & Bacon | date = 1998 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Corr | first1 = Charles A. | first2 = Kenneth J. | last2 = Doka | first3 = Robert | last3 = Kastenbaum | name-list-format = vanc | date = 1999 | title = Dying and Its Interpreters: A Review of Selected Literature and Some Comments on the State of the Field. | journal = OMEGA: Journal of Death and Dying | volume = 39 | issue = 4 | pages = 239\u2013259 | doi = 10.2190/3KGF-52BV-QTNT-UBMX }}</ref>\n* The existence of these stages as such has not been demonstrated.\n* No evidence has been presented that people actually do move from Stage 1 through Stage 5.\n* The limitations of the method have not been acknowledged.\n* The line is blurred between description and prescription.\n* The resources, pressures, and characteristics of the immediate environment, which can make a tremendous difference, are not taken into account.\n\nA 2003 study of bereaved individuals conducted by Maciejewski and colleagues at [[Yale University]] obtained some findings consistent with the five-stage hypothesis but others inconsistent with it. Several letters were also published in the same journal criticizing this research and arguing against the stage idea.<ref name=\"Jama\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Maciejewski PK, Zhang B, Block SD, Prigerson HG | title = An empirical examination of the stage theory of grief | journal = JAMA | volume = 297 | issue = 7 | pages = 716\u201323 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17312291 | doi = 10.1001/jama.297.7.716 }}</ref>\n\n[[George Bonanno]], Professor of Clinical Psychology at Columbia University, in his book ''The Other Side of Sadness: What the New Science of Bereavement Tells Us About Life After a Loss'',<ref name=\"Bonanno2009\">{{cite book|last=Bonanno|first=George | name-list-format = vanc |authorlink=George Bonanno |title=The Other Side of Sadness: What the New Science of Bereavement Tells Us about Life After Loss|url=https://archive.org/details/othersideofsadne00bona|url-access=registration|year=2009|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=978-0-465-01360-9}}</ref> summarizes [[peer-review]]ed research based on thousands of subjects over two decades and concludes that a natural [[psychological resilience]] is a principal component of grief<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bonanno GA | title = Loss, trauma, and human resilience: have we underestimated the human capacity to thrive after extremely aversive events? | journal = The American Psychologist | volume = 59 | issue = 1 | pages = 20\u20138 | date = January 2004 | pmid = 14736317 | doi = 10.1037/0003-066X.59.1.20 | url = http://rcin.org.pl/Content/60213 }}</ref> and that there are no stages of grief to pass.  Bonanno's work has also demonstrated that absence of grief or trauma symptoms is a healthy outcome.<ref name=\"scientificamerican1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Stix G | title = The neuroscience of true grit | journal = Scientific American | volume = 304 | issue = 3 | pages = 28\u201333 | date = March 2011 | pmid = 21438486 | doi = 10.1038/scientificamerican0311-28 | bibcode = 2011SciAm.304c..28S }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nThe lack of support in peer-reviewed research or objective clinical observation by many practitioners in the field has led to the labels of ''myth'' and ''fallacy'' in the notion that there are stages of grief.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2042372-2,00.html|title=New Ways to Think About Grief|first=Ruth Davis|last=Konigsberg | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 29, 2011|publisher=|access-date=November 27, 2016|via=www.time.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/five-fallacies-of-grief/ |title=Five Fallacies of Grief: Debunking Psychological Stages |publisher=[[Scientific American]] |date=2008-11-01 |access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| vauthors = Corr CA |date=23 October 2018|title=The 'five stages' in coping with dying and bereavement: strengths, weaknesses and some alternatives|url=|journal=Mortality|volume=24|issue=4|pages=405\u2013417|doi=10.1080/13576275.2018.1527826}}</ref> Nevertheless, the model's use has persisted in popular news and entertainment media.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | vauthors = K\u00fcbler-Ross E | date = 1969 | title = On Death and Dying | publisher = Routledge | isbn = 0-415-04015-9 }}\n* {{cite book | vauthors = K\u00fcbler-Ross E | date = 2005 | title = On Grief and Grieving: Finding the Meaning of Grief Through the Five Stages of Loss | publisher = Simon & Schuster | isbn = 0-7432-6344-8 }}\n* {{cite book | vauthors = Scire P | date = 2007 | title = Applying Grief Stages to Organizational Change }}\n* {{cite thesis | vauthors = Brent MR | title = An Attributional Analysis of K\u00fcbler-Ross' Model of Dying | degree= Master's | publisher = Harvard University | date = 1981 | oclc = 77003423}}\n* {{cite book | first = Johannes Hendrikus | last = Van der Poel | name-list-format = vanc | title = An Evaluation of the Relevance of the K\u00fcbler-Ross Model to the Post-injury Responses of Competitive Athletes | publisher = [[University of the Free State]] | date =  2000 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ekrfoundation.org/ Elisabeth K\u00fcbler-Ross Foundation]\n* [http://dying.about.com/od/glossary/g/DABDA.htm DABDA: The Five Stages of Coping With Death] \u2013 [[About.com]]\n* [http://www.healthy.net/scr/interview.aspx?Id=205 \"On Death and Dying\"] \u2013 interview with Elisabeth K\u00fcbler-Ross M.D.\n* [http://home.windstream.net/overbeck/grfbrf13.html \"Beware the Five Stages of 'Grief{{'\"}}] \u2013 TLC Group editorial\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kubler-Ross Model}}\n[[Category:Grief]]\n[[Category:Psychological theories]]\n[[Category:Stage theories]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kubler-ross-grief-cycle-1-728.jpg|thumb|400px|The five stages of grief according to the K\u00fcbler-Ross model]]\n\nThe '''K\u00fcbler-Ross model''', or the '''five stages of grief''', postulates a series of emotions experienced by terminally ill patients prior to [[death]], or people who have lost a loved one, wherein the five stages are: [[denial]], [[anger]], bargaining, [[Depression (mood)|depression]],  and [[acceptance]]. Although commonly referenced in popular media, the existence of these stages has not been demonstrated and the model is not considered helpful in explaining the grieving process.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Bonanno2009\" />\n\nThe model was first introduced by Swiss-American psychiatrist [[Elisabeth K\u00fcbler-Ross]] in her 1969 book ''[[On Death and Dying]]'', and was inspired by her work with [[Terminal illness|terminally ill]] patients.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,689491,00.html |title= Milestones |date=August 30, 2004 | work=TIME | first=Sarah M. | last=Broom | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> Motivated by the lack of instruction in medical schools on the subject of death and dying, K\u00fcbler-Ross examined death and those faced with it at the [[University of Chicago]]'s [[Pritzker School of Medicine|medical school]]. K\u00fcbler-Ross' project evolved into a series of seminars which, along with patient interviews and previous research, became the foundation for her book.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uky.edu/~cperring/kr.htm |title=PHI350: The Stages in the Dying Process |first=Christian |last=Perring | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Although K\u00fcbler-Ross is commonly credited with creating stage models, earlier  bereavement theorists and clinicians such as [[Erich Lindemann]], [[Colin Murray Parkes|Collin Murray Parkes]], and [[John Bowlby]] used similar models of stages of phases as early as the 1940s.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Bereavement groups and the role of social support: integrating theory, research, and practice |last=Hoy |first=William G. | name-list-format = vanc |date=2016 |publisher=Routledge/Taylor and Francis |isbn=9781317416357 |location=New York |oclc=942843686}}</ref>\n\nLater in her life, K\u00fcbler-Ross noted that the stages are not a linear and predictable progression and that she regretted writing them in a way that was misunderstood.<ref name=GriefGrieving /> \"K\u00fcbler-Ross originally saw these stages as reflecting how people cope with illness and dying,\" observed grief researcher Kenneth J. Doka, \"not